        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "We have the current state. Now we need to write main.cpp to tie everything together. Also need to review any missing pieces: Sensor.h needs getMoisture? Actually WebServer uses readPercent, readRaw, readVoltage - those exist. Calibration has getDryValue, setDryValue, resetToDefaults. Display has begin, showStatus, showCalibrationScreen, showMessage, deepSleep. WebServer constructor takes pointers. \n\nWe need to add the Sensor, Calibration, Display objects in main.cpp, call begin() on each, and in loop call WebServer::handleClient(), and periodically update display with sensor data.\n\nAlso need to implement a timer for display updates (every 10 seconds maybe) to avoid excessive e-ink refreshes.\n\nAlso need to handle calibration mode: maybe show calibration screen when calibrating? We could have a button press on a GPIO to start calibration sequence? Or just rely on web API. For now, keep it simple: just web API.\n\nWe also need to read current raw value when calibrating - the web server already reads fresh raw value on each POST.\n\nPotential issues: \n- WebServer constructor takes Sensor*, Calibration*, Display* but in main we need to create those objects before WebServer. Order: Sensor, Calibration, Display, WebServer.\n- Preferences used in Calibration and WebServer - they need different namespace names. Calibration uses \"calib\", WebServer uses \"wifi\". That's fine.\n- In WebServer::setupRoutes, the events endpoint is defined but not used. Can leave.\n- The POST /wifi/connect uses preferences.putString which uses the opened namespace \"wifi\". But in WebServer::begin() we open preferences(\"wifi\", false) and never close it. That's okay.\n- But Calibration also uses Preferences with namespace \"calib\". They won't conflict.\n\nNow let's write main.cpp.\n\nPseudo:\n#include <Arduino.h>\n#include \"Sensor.h\"\n#include \"Calibration.h\"\n#include \"Display.h\"\n#include \"WebServer.h\"\n\nSensor sensor(4); // GPIO4 for moisture sensor\nCalibration calibration;\nDisplay display;\nWebServer webServer(&sensor, &calibration, &display);\n\nunsigned long lastDisplayUpdate = 0;\nconst unsigned long DISPLAY_UPDATE_INTERVAL = 10000; // 10 seconds\n\nvoid setup() {\n  Serial.begin(115200);\n  delay(1000);\n  Serial.println(\"Polivator v1.0 starting...\");\n  \n  sensor.begin();\n  calibration.begin();\n  display.begin();\n  \n  // Load calibration into sensor\n  sensor.setCalibration(calibration.getDryValue(), calibration.getWetValue());\n  \n  webServer.begin();\n  \n  // Initial display update\n  display.showStatus(sensor.readPercent(), sensor.readRaw(), false, WiFi.status() == WL_CONNECTED ? \"connected\" : \"disconnected\");\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n  webServer.handleClient();\n  \n  // Update sensor readings periodically\n  static unsigned long lastRead = 0;\n  if (millis() - lastRead > 2000) {\n    lastRead = millis();\n    float moisture = sensor.readPercent();\n    int raw = sensor.readRaw();\n    // Could also update calibration if it changed? But calibration is stored in NVS, sensor.setCalibration only called once.\n    // Optionally reload calibration periodically? Not necessary.\n    \n    // Update display at a slower rate\n    if (millis() - lastDisplayUpdate > DISPLAY_UPDATE_INTERVAL) {\n      lastDisplayUpdate = millis();\n      String wifiStatus = WiFi.status() == WL_CONNECTED ? \"connected\" : (WiFi.getMode() == WIFI_AP ? \"ap\" : \"disconnected\");\n      display.showStatus(moisture, raw, false, wifiStatus.c_str());\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nBut we need to include WiFi.h for WiFi.status() in main. Or we can get wifi status via webServer? No, just include WiFi.h.\n\nAlso, need to handle case where calibration changes via web API - sensor should reflect new thresholds. Since sensor.setCalibration is called only in setup, new calibration from web will be saved to NVS but sensor won't use it until reboot. That's not ideal. We can either: (1) call sensor.setCalibration after each calibration change in WebServer callbacks, or (2) have sensor always read thresholds from Calibration object directly. Option 1 is easier: in WebServer callbacks, after setting calibration, also call m_sensor->setCalibration(m_calibration->getDryValue(), m_calibration->getWetValue()). We'll add that.\n\nLet's edit WebServer.cpp to add that line in the three calibration routes.\n\nAlso need to make sure Sensor.h includes setCalibration with correct signature. Currently: setCalibration(int dry, int wet) but Calibration returns uint16_t. That's fine (int can hold up to 65535). We'll leave as is.\n\nWe should also make Sensor::readVoltage return float (voltage = raw * 3.3 / 4095). That's already done.\n\nNow let's implement main.cpp.\n\nAlso need to consider display deepSleep? Not necessary for now.\n\nLet's also add a \"Calibrating\" flag management? Not needed for basic functionality.\n\nProceed to write main.cpp and update WebServer.cpp.",
