        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "We have completed the initial implementation. Now we need to verify that the code compiles and is consistent. Let's do a final review of all files, check for missing includes, and ensure the project structure is correct.\n\nWe have:\n- platformio.ini ok\n- src/main.cpp uses correct APIs now\n- lib/Sensor/ ok (setCalibration needs int params but other code passes int which is fine)\n- lib/Calibration/ ok (uses Preferences)\n- lib/Display/ ok (GxEPD2, but note: GxEPD2_213_BN might require specific class name. WeAct 2.13\" e-paper uses SSD1680. The library supports it. We used GxEPD2_213_BN. That should be correct for WeActStudio 2.13\".)\n- lib/WebServer/ ok\n\nPotential issues:\n1. Display constructor uses `m_display(EINK_CS, EINK_DC, EINK_RST, EINK_BUSY)` but GxEPD2_BW constructor also needs an SPI reference? The GxEPD2 template takes pin parameters: EPD_CS, EPD_DC, EPD_RST, EPD_BUSY. Actually the driver class GxEPD2_213_BN constructor takes (CS, DC, RST, BUSY). But the SPI bus must be initialized. In Arduino, using hardware SPI, need to call SPI.begin() before display init. Also need to set SPI pins for ESP32-S3. The default SPI pins are VSPI: MOSI=11, MISO=13, SCK=12, CS=10. But we defined EINK_MOSI=11, EINK_SCLK=12. For GxEPD2, it uses the default SPI bus unless we pass a reference. We should explicitly set SPI pins and call SPI.begin() in Display::begin(). Also the constructor of the display does not start the display; SPI needs to be configured first.\n\nIn Display::begin(), we should add:\nSPI.begin(EINK_SCLK, -1, EINK_MOSI, EINK_CS); // SCLK, MISO (unused), MOSI, CS (CS is handled by driver but we set it for SPI bus config)\nActually the driver handles CS control itself. We need to configure SPI with the correct pins. For ESP32, before using any SPI devices, you can call SPI.begin(SCLK, MISO, MOSI, CS) to set the pins. But the display driver may call SPI.begin() with default pins if not called. To be safe, in Display::begin(), before m_display.init(), call SPI.begin(EINK_SCLK, -1, EINK_MOSI, EINK_CS); (MISO is optional, -1 for not used). This ensures correct pins on ESP32-S3.\n\nAlternatively, we can rely on the default SPI pins (MOSI=11, SCLK=12, CS=10 as per our defines). But the board might have different default. We should explicitly set them.\n\nAlso, the GxEPD2 library expects the CS pin to be passed to the constructor, and it will control it. The SPI bus initialization with CS pin sets the default CS for SPI transactions, but the driver likely does its own CS manipulation. Better to not pass CS to SPI.begin: use SPI.begin(SCLK, MISO, MOSI). Actually SPI.begin with CS pin only affects the default chip select line used by SPI.transfer but the driver uses separate digitalWrite for CS. So it's safe to set SPI pins without CS.\n\n2. WiFi: In WebServer::begin(), after preferences.begin, we use preferences.getString which requires namespace opened. That's fine.\n\n3. In WebServer::setupRoutes(), the DNS server uses dnsServer variable. Need to add DNSServer dnsServer; as member of WebServer class. Let's check WebServer.h header.\n\nCurrently WebServer.h likely has proper declarations? Let's read it.",
