dex 0 (first sensor). For now, main.cpp just uses index 0 for serial. That's acceptable.\n\nBut we need to read the updated sensor.h to see the exact API. Let's read it.\n\nWe also need to read the updated WebServer.h to see the constructor signature.\n\nLet me just plan: we'll rewrite main.cpp to use SensorManager. The sensor pins: we can define an array of pin numbers in main.cpp or in Types.h. The user wants 5 sensors. We'll hardcode pins array, e.g., {6, 7, 8, 9, 10} (or {6,1,2,3,4}). Choose GPIOs that are safe for ADC1: GPIO1-10. We'll use pins {6,7,8,9,10} (but GPIO10 is strapping pin that can cause boot issues if pulled low; but it's used as output? Actually GPIO10 is strapping pin for S3? On S3, GPIO3 is strapping for JTAG? Better avoid strapping pins: GPIO0, GPIO1, GPIO2, GPIO3, GPIO4, GPIO5 are safe? Actually on ESP32-S3: GPIO0, GPIO2, GPIO3, GPIO4, GPIO5, GPIO6, GPIO7, GPIO8, GPIO9 are not strapping? Let me check typical: GPIO0 is boot (strapping), GPIO1, GPIO2, GPIO3, GPIO4, GPIO5 are fine for ADC. GPIO6 is fine. I'll use GPIO1, GPIO2, GPIO3, GPIO4, GPIO6 as 5 pins. Or allow user to configure in platformio.ini build flags? For now, we'll define an array in main.cpp.\n\nBut better: let Calibration store pin numbers for each sensor index (in SensorConfig). Then SensorManager uses those pins. In calibration.begin(), we can set default pins for each index: {6,1,2,3,4} or something. But the user may have wired differently. So we should allow setting pin per sensor. We can add a method: calibration->setPin(index, pin). And include it in SensorConfig. Then we could provide a serial command or web API to change pin. For simplicity, we'll hardcode pins in main.cpp and pass them to sensorManager.begin(&calibration, pins, count). But sensorManager.begin currently takes Calibration* and then reads pins from calibration. So we need calibration to contain default pins. Let's incorporate pin into calibration. In the refactored Calibration, I didn't see setPin method. But it does have getConfig/setConfig which include pin? In Types.h SensorConfig has pin. So yes, calibration stores pin. So we need to set default pins in Calibration::begin.\n\nWe'll update Calibration::begin to initialize default pins for each index: e.g., 6,1,2,3,4. Then sensorManager.begin(calibration) reads them.\n\nNow main.cpp will be rewritten.\n\nWe need to read the updated Sensor.h and WebServer.h to see the exact API.\n\nLet's do that via read-file.",
