        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "We need to refactor the code to support multiple sensors. From the summary of the existing files (they were not returned in full but summary indicates existing structure). However the summary mentions \"Calibration, SensorManager, WebServer, Display, main.cpp\". But the current code on disk is from before: single sensor. We must do a comprehensive refactoring. The summary says there is a `Types.h` missing and methods mismatches. So we need to create a multi-sensor architecture. Let's design:\n\n- `SensorConfig` struct: name[32], pin (ADC channel), dryCal, wetCal, rawValue, calibratedPercent.\n- `SensorManager` class: holds array of SensorConfig (up to MAX_SENSORS=5), performs ADC reads, applies calibration, exposes getters and setters.\n- `Calibration` class: using Preferences to store/load per-sensor configurations (dry, wet, name, pin). We'll store each sensor config as a JSON string under key \"sensor0\", \"sensor1\"... or use NVS blobs.\n- `WebServer` class: already has all routes; update to work with SensorManager and Calibration. Add routes for /api/sensors, /api/calibrate/{index}, /api/config/{index}.\n- `Display` class: update to show list of sensors.\n- `main.cpp`: instantiate SensorManager with pin list, pass to other components.\n\nWe need to create a `Types.h` file that defines MAX_SENSORS and SensorConfig struct. Or we can put in Calibration or Sensor.\n\nLet's proceed step by step.\n\nStep 2: Create Types.h and refactor Preferences (Calibration) to store per-sensor data. We'll store each sensor as a Preferences \"space\" or use a single key per sensor.\n\nSimpler: Use Preferences namespace \"sensors\" and for each sensor index store a JSON string or binary blob. But JSON on NVS is heavy. Better: Use separate keys per field: \"dry0\", \"wet0\", \"name0\", \"pin0\", etc. But that's messy. Since we have limited size (up to 5), we can store all in one key as a JSON array using ArduinoJson. But ArduinoJson 7 has doc capacity. We can serialize a JsonDocument to string and store as a single key. Use Preferences namespace \"calib\", key \"config\". That's fine.\n\nSo:\n- In Calibration, we keep Preferences, but now have a `loadAllConfigs(SensorConfig* configs, uint8_t max)` and `saveAllConfigs(SensorConfig* configs, uint8_t count)`. Also individual get/set methods.\n\nWe'll also create a `SensorConfig` struct in Types.h.\n\nLet's also consider the pin definitions: we need to store the assigned pins for each sensor. They can be defined at compile time in main.cpp (e.g., int sensorPins[MAX_SENSORS] = {1,2,3,4,6};) and it's also stored in NVS so firmware can change via web? Not in first version. But we can store pins in NVS too for flexibility. But for simplicity, pins are set at compile time and stored/read from there. Web UI will not allow changing pin assignment (hardware wiring is fixed). So we skip pin storage in NVS.\n\nThus each sensor has: dry, wet, name. The pin is defined in main.cpp.\n\nImplementation plan for step 2:\n\n1. Create `lib/Common/Types.h` with:\n   - `#define MAX_SENSORS 5`\n   - `struct SensorConfig { char name[32]; uint8_t pin; int dryRaw; int wetRaw; };`\n\n2. Refactor `Calibration` class:\n   - Remove old `Preferences` uses for single. \n   - Rename `Calibration` to `CalibrationManager`? or keep.\n   - Methods: \n     - `CalibrationManager()` (constructor with Preferences namespace)\n     - `void begin()` - open preferences \"calib\"\n     - `void loadAll(SensorConfig* configs, uint8_t count)` - read JSON string from key \"all\", parse into array. If not present, set defaults (dry=3000, wet=1200, name=\"Sensor\").\n     - `void saveAll(SensorConfig* configs, uint8_t count)` - serialize to JSON string, store in \"all\".\n     - `void getSensorConfig(uint8_t index, SensorConfig& cfg)` - load single\n     - `void setSensorConfig(uint8_t index, const SensorConfig& cfg)` - modify in memory then saveAll? Or modify and save immediate.\n   - Use DynamicJsonDocument (or plain JsonDocument) with capacity e.g. 500 bytes.\n\n3. In `main.cpp`, include Types.h.\n\nBut careful: we also need to keep backward compatibility? No, we're refactoring.\n\nLet's do step 2 now: create Types.h and refactor Calibration.\n\nBut the code agent said \"Types.h missing\". So we need to create it. Let's proceed.",
