        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "We have made many changes. Probably more inconsistencies remain with the refactor. Let's check Calibration.h currently.\n\nWe have:\n- begin(const uint8_t* defaultPins, uint8_t count)\n- loadAllConfigs(...)\n- saveAllConfigs(...)\n- setDryRaw, setWetRaw\n- setName(uint8_t index, const char* name)\n- uint8_t getPin uint8_t index) const\n- int getDryValue(uint8_t index) const\n- int getWetValue(uint8_t index) const\n- const char* getName(uint8_t index) const\n- setDryValue, setWetValue, resetToDefaults (added)\n\nWe need to ensure that in begin, when we call loadAllConfigs, the configs' pins are set from defaultPins. In our implementation of Calibration::begin, we have:\n\n```cpp\nvoid Calibration::begin(const uint8_t* defaultPins, uint8_t count) {\n    m_count = count > MAX_SENSORS ? MAX_SENSORS : count;\n    loadAllConfigs(m_configs, defaultPins, count);\n}\n```\n\nThen loadAllConfigs: if prefs key exists, deserialize and assign, else initialize m_configs with defaults (dry=3000, wet=1200, name=\"Sensor N\", pin from defaultPins). Good.\n\nNow, we must ensure SensorManager::begin calls cal->getPin(i), getDryValue(i), getWetValue(i). Those are now available. However, we must ensure that Calibration has been started before SensorManager uses it. We'll order in main.cpp: calibration.begin(pins, count); then sensorManager.begin(&calibration); That's correct.\n\nNow check SensorManager::begin: duplicates the calibration data into sensorState. That's fine.\n\nNow check WebServer.cpp: uses m_calibration->getDryValue(i), getWetValue(i), getName(i) — all present. Uses m_sensorManager->getRaw(i), getPercent(i), getVoltage(i) — all present.\n\nIssues to verify:\n\n1. In WebServer.cpp sendStatusEvent and /api/status handler: they call getRaw(i), getPercent(i), getVoltage(i) — yes, those methods exist. They call getName(i) — exists.\n\n2. In the /api/calibrate/dry endpoint: they call setDryValue(index, raw) and then getDryValue/getWetValue — setDryValue exists (alias). Good.\n\n3. In /api/calibrate/wet: similar: setWetValue exists. But line 140 previously had readRaw, we fixed to getRaw.\n\n4. In /api/calibrate/reset: resetToDefaults exists.\n\n5. In /api/config/sensor: setName with const char* works.\n\n6. The calibration routes use pathArgs. Are we sure that `{index}` in server.on(... \"/api/calibrate/dry/{index}\" ...) will capture correctly? ESPAsyncWebServer supports path parameters like `:index`. The actual syntax for ESPAsyncWebServer is `server.on(\"/api/calibrate/dry/{index}\")` — but does it support that? Standard syntax is `/api/calibrate/dry/{param}` but in ESPAsyncWebServer, you use `server.on(\"/api/calibrate/dry/:index\", ...)` with colon, and then request->pathArg(0) gets the value. I need to check if `{...}` syntax is supported. I think ESPAsyncWebServer only supports `:param` syntax, not `{param}`. This is a potential bug. We should change routes to use `/:index` syntax.\n\nBut note that currently in the code we have `\"/api/calibrate/dry/{index}\"`. Not sure if it works. Let's check ESPAsyncWebServer documentation: it uses `:param` for path parameters. So we must change to `/:index` (or `/{index}`? I think it's `:index`). Many examples: `server.on(\"/api/data/:id\", ...)`. Yes, correct syntax is colon, not curly braces. We should update routes.\n\nAlso, we need to ensure we include <ESPAsyncWebServer.h> which we do.\n\n7. Also need to check that SendStatusEvent signature changed: it now takes SensorManager* but we call it from main.cpp with `webServer.sendStatusEvent(&sensorManager)`. The implementation uses `sensorManager-> getRaw(i) etc.` OK.\n\n8. Check Display: It currently has `showStatus(float moisturePercent, int rawValue, bool calibrating, const char* wifiStatus)`. We are passing float and int. That's fine. In main.cpp we pass sensorManager.getPercent(0) (returns int) to a float param — automatic conversion fine. But we haven't changed Display to show multiple sensors yet. The user might want that, but for now at least it shows first sensor. However, the user asked to show field name. We may need to update Display to show list of sensors. But for compilation it's fine.\n\n9. Check that we have all necessary includes in main.cpp: we include \"Sensor.h\" which includes \"Common/Types.h\". That should bring in MAX_SENSORS. Also include \"Calibration.h\" etc.\n\n10. Check that the `display.showCalibrationScreen()` calls now have a parameter (const char* step). In Calibration.h, we have `showCalibrationScreen(const char* step = \"\")` with default empty string. In main.cpp we call `display.showCalibrationScreen(\"Calibration mode\")` and `display.showCalibrationScreen()` (in non-calibrating block? Actually in loop under calibrating we call `display.showCalibrationScreen(\"Calibration mode\")`. In the non-calibrating block we call `display.showStatus(...)`. So we have removed the old calls without constant. In the old code, there was `display.showCalibrationScreen();` without argument. That still works due to default parameter. Good.\n\n11. One more issue: in main.cpp we removed the if (calibrating) block that prevents non-calibrating showStatus with calibrating flag. But in the new loop we have:\n\n```cpp\nif (calibrating) {\n    display.showCalibrationScreen(\"Calibration mode\");\n} else {\n    display.showStatus(sensorManager.getPercent(0), sensorManager.getRaw(0), false, wifiStatus);\n}\n```\n\nSo we don't pass calibrating flag to showStatus anymore. The third parameter in showStatus is bool calibrating. We set it to false. That's okay.\n\n12. Potential issue: Serial commands in main.cpp: we now read a character and if >= '0' && <= '4' select sensor. But note: after selecting sensor, we return, so next character will be command. The old code used calibration mode flag. We added selection. Should work.\n\n13. Need to check that in the loop, sensorManager.readAll() is called every 2 seconds. In the old code, it was not called; we used the sensor object dire