        "content": "The user has several issues to address:\n\n1. The e-ink display shows red color - but they have a tri-color (black, white, red) display. They want only black and white. The current code uses `GxEPD2_213_BN` which is the black/white variant. But the user says their display is tri-color. This is confusing. Looking at GxEPD2 library, there are different display types. `GxEPD2_213_BN` is for the 2.13\" black/white display. But the user mentions red - perhaps they have `GxEPD2_213_B73` or similar tri-color. Let me check what WeActStudio 2.13\" offers. WeAct 2.13\" typically comes in two versions: black/white (4 gray levels) and black/white/red (tri-color). The library has `GxEPD2_213_B73` for the tri-color version. But the user said \"три цвета - черный, белый и красный\" so it's tri-color. They want only black and white though. The solution is to use the correct display type but ensure we only use black and white colors. Actually `GxEPD2_BW` template class is for black/white displays. For tri-color displays, there's `GxEPD2_3C` or `GxEPD2_213_B73` (which inherits from GxEPD2_3C). But the display might still work in BW mode if we don't use red. However the issue might be that the display is actually a tri-color display and the code is initializing it as BW, causing color distortion. \n\nWait, let me think again. If the display is tri-color (black, white, red) and we use `GxEPD2_213_BN` which is for BW-only, the library might still work but the \"red\" color might appear because some tri-color displays use red as the second color when driven incorrectly. Actually, for tri-color e-paper, there's separate red ink. If you try to use it as BW-only, the red state might be left undefined or show as red. \n\nThe correct approach: Use `GxEPD2_3C` or `GxEPD2_213_B73` (if that's the exact model) and only use black and white colors (never use `GxEPD2_RED`). But the template `GxEPD2_BW` is strictly for BW displays. If the display is tri-color, we should use `GxEPD