supports partial updates with `display(true)` for fast refresh, but e-ink displays still need a full refresh every N updates to prevent ghosting. I can implement a simple approach: do partial refresh for minor updates, and full refresh every 10-20 updates.\n\nBut actually, for the e-ink display, partial refresh is tricky and might not work well on all displays. The GxEPD2 library supports it via `m_display.setPartialWindow()` and `m_display.nextPage()`. However, for full screen updates, we can use `m_display.display(true)` for fast refresh (skips the white flash) but still redraws everything. The true/false parameter in `display()` controls whether to do a fast refresh (skip white flash) - this is supported on many e-ink panels including the WeAct 2.13\".\n\nActually, looking at GxEPD2 API: `display(bool partial_update_mode)` where true enables partial update mode (faster, no full flash), false does full refresh (with flash). For simple text changes, partial update mode works fine but may show ghosting after many updates. A good strategy: use partial update for routine updates, full refresh every 20 updates.\n\nLet me now plan the changes needed:\n\n1. **Display.h/cpp**: \n   - Change from `GxEPD2_213_BN` to `GxEPD2_213_B73` (or appropriate tri-color model) and use `GxEPD2_3C` template instead of `GxEPD2_BW`.\n   - Actually let me check if `GxEPD2_213_BN` is the right model. The \"BN\" suffix might mean black/white without red. The tri-color version would be different. Let me search the GxEPD2 library for WeAct 2.13 tri-color. I recall `GxEPD2_213_Z19c` or `GxEPD2_213_B73` or `GxEPD2_213_B74`. I need to be precise.\n\n   Actually, since user says they have a tri-color but want BW only, I can simply ensure we never use red color in drawing. But the problem might be that using `GxEPD2_BW` template on a tri-color display causes undefined behavior. The correct approach is to use `GxEPD2_3C` template with the proper display class, and only draw in black and white. Let me