        "content": "We need to read the remaining lines 301-306 (the closing HTML and rawliteral). Also read WebServer.cpp for the current routes. Before writing code, we should understand what we have and then plan the modifications.\n\nThe main issues:\n\n1. Display shows red because it uses `GxEPD2_BW` but the display is tri-color? Actually, the user said \"у него три цвета - черный, белый и красный\" (it has three colors - black, white and red). The current code uses `GxEPD2_BW` with `GxEPD2_213_BN` which is a black/white display class. But their display is the WeActStudio 2.13\" which is a three-color type (black/white/red). `GxEPD2_213_BN` is for B/W only; for B/W/R they might need `GxEPD2_213_B73` or similar? Actually, GxEPD2 supports many displays. The user wants black/white only, no red. The issue is that the display hardware might be a three-color panel, and if you initialize it as B/W, it might still work but sometimes shows red? Or if we use `GxEPD2_BW` with a three-color screen, it should display only black and white but maybe the initialization waveform causes red flashes? The user said \"сейчас он почему то красным отображает на экране\", meaning it shows red content. This could be because we are using `GxEPD2_213_BN` which is correct for B/W, but the panel itself might be the B73 variant (which is B/W/R) and the library chooses the wrong LUT. To get B/W only, we should use the B/W class but the correct display type. For WeActStudio 2.13\" tri-color, the typical types are `GxEPD2_213_B73` (for B/W/R) using `GxEPD2_3C` class. But if we want only B/W, we could still use `GxEPD2_BW` with the B/W type? Actually, the physical display is either B/W or B/W/R. If the user's display is the B/W/R variant, then using `GxEPD2_BW` might cause issues because the panel expects three-color commands. We should switch to `GxEPD2_3C` and `GxEPD2_213_B73`, but then we need to only draw in black and white (not red) – which is already the case. However, the user sees red, meaning the display is showing something in red that wasn't intended. Likely the library initializes with a full display update that flashes all colors (including red). To fix this, we can:\n\n- Use `GxEPD2_3C` with `GxEPD2_213_B73` (the tri-color type). Then we will only write to black and white. Or we could use `GxEPD2_BW` but the panel might be incompatible. Let's check GxEPD2 documentation: For the WeActStudio 2.13\" (SSD1680) there are two variants: with red (B73) and without (BN). The user says it has three colors, so it's the B73 variant. Use `GxEPD2_3C<GxEPD2_213_B73, GxEPD2_213_B73::HEIGHT>`.\n\nBut we also need to ensure no red is drawn. `GxEPD2_3C` supports `GxEPD_RED` and `GxEPD_BLACK`, `GxEPD_WHITE`. If we only set text and fill to `GxEPD_BLACK` and `GxEPD_WHITE`, it should be B/W. But the issue might be due to partial refresh or something else.\n\nSimpler: The user wants to disable red completely. We can use `GxEPD2_BW` but maybe the display type should be `GxEPD2_213_B73` with `GxEPD2_BW`? That would be wrong. Need to use `GxEPD2_3C` because the panel is three-color.\n\nThus we change `GxEPD2_BW` to `GxEPD2_3C` and `GxEPD2_213_BN` to `GxEPD2_213_B73`. Then in drawing code, we only use `GxEPD_BLACK` and `GxEPD_WHITE`. That should eliminate red.\n\nAlternatively, we could keep `GxEPD2_BW` but force the display to be black/white by using the correct display type. GxEPD2 supports `GxEPD2_213_BN` for B/W only. If the hardware is tri-color but the driver is BN, the library might misconfigure the display and cause artifacts. So better to switch.\n\n2. Remove \"Moisture Monitor\" title: delete line 33 and shift y-start up.\n\n3. Implement change-based updates: currently `showStatus` does a full refresh every time. We want to only update when something changed. Need to store previous values in the Display class (or in main.cpp). Since the display class is called from main loop with current values, we can store the last displayed values as member variables and compare. If same, skip displaying. But we also need to invalidate after a full update? We can store a flag `m_dirty` and also compare sensor values. When entering showStatus, compare with previous values; if any differs, set m_dirty. Then if dirty, do a partial refresh (or full refresh). Actually, for partial update, we can use `setPartialWindow` and `display(true)`. But if the display has tri-color, partial updates might not work perfectly. However, for B/W only, partial updates on tri-color panels may work. We can implement:\n\n- store last: `uint8_t m_lastPercentages[MAX_SENSORS]`, `int m_lastRaw[MAX_SENSORS]`, `char m_lastWifiStatus[32]`, etc.\n- In showStatus, compare; if any change, update the changed areas via partial window. For simplicity, if only percentage changed, we can just update the text area for that sensor. But implementing full partial update is complex. A simpler approach: keep a dirty flag per sensor and only update the specific lines. Or do a full refresh every time but use `display(true)` which does a fast refresh (without full erase). That might be acceptable and reduces complexity. We can just change `display(false)` to `display(true)` for fast refresh, and only call `display` if the values changed. But `display(true)` on tri-color might still cause flashing? We'll test.\n\nAlternative: just compare and skip entirely if no change. That reduces updates to display. For partial window, we need to redraw only the changed text area. GxEPD2 supports `setPartialWindow()`. We can define for each sensor a box (x, y, w, h) and update only that region. That's advanced. For now, we can:\n\n- Store previous display buffer? Not efficient.\n\nGiven time, we'll implement simple: only call display if any value changed, using full window fast refresh `display(true)` instead of `display(false)`. This will reduce unnecessary updates. Also, when no change, we do nothing.\n\nBut the user said \"обновлять экран надло только тогда когда есть изменение и делать это через быстрый рефреш\" – update only when there is change and do it through fast refresh. So we need to detect change, and if changed, do fast refresh (partial). We can store the previous string representation? Or compare numbers.\n\nBest: store previous percentages and raw values, and the wifiStatus string. In showStatus, compare; if any diff, setFullWindow, fill, draw all, then `display(true)` (fast). If no diff, return early without drawing.\n\n4. Web interface: need to add WiFi settings page. Currently the web UI is a simple page with sensor cards. Need to add a button that expands a section for WiFi settings: current SSID, change SSID/password, maybe a list of networks scanned. However, scanning WiFi from ESPAsyncWebServer is complex. Simpler: provide a modal or section to enter new SSID/password and submit to a route. The routes already exist: `POST /api/wifi/config` with body `ssid` and `password`. The code in WebServer.cpp likely handles that. We need to check. Also need to get current status (connected SSID). We can add a route `GET /api/wifi/status` that returns current ssid and ip. Then in JS, fetch that and display.\n\nAlso, the index.h uses `fetch('/api/config/sensor/${index}', ...)` with path parameter, but we earlier changed routes to use query parameters (`index=...`). The JS in index.h still uses path parameter syntax, which is broken. Need to fix those fetch URLs to use query parameters. Also `calibrateDry`, `calibrateWet`, `calibrateReset` endpoints are `POST /api/calibrate/dry/{index}` but we changed to query. So the web UI is broken. Need to update the JS to send `POST /api/calibrate/dry?index=${index}`. Also sensor config: `POST /api/config/sensor?index=${index}`.\n\nThus we need to rewrite the JS to fix URLs and add WiFi settings.\n\nWe'll edit index.h with a comprehensive update.\n\nAlso need to adjust WebServer.cpp to handle the new routes (actually they already use query params). But we should check if there is a route for WiFi config. Let's read WebServer.cpp.\n\nGiven the plan, step 2/3/4/5 can be done in one code agent call, but we need to split per dependencies. Step 2 (Display.h/Display.cpp) and step 4 (index.h, WebServer.cpp) can be done in parallel after step 1 read completed. But we can combine step 2 and 3 as they are both Display changes. Step 4 and 5 are web changes. So we can send one code agent for Display changes and another for Web changes (though we can only have one code agent per turn). But we can combine all into one code agent call as it's a lot but the agent can handle it. However, we need to read WebServer.cpp first.\n\nLet's read remaining index.h and WebServer.cpp.\n\nRead offset 301-306 of index.h, and WebServer.cpp. Use bulk actions.",
