        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "We have a few issues to fix:\n\n1. Display shows red color (tri-color display). The display is WeActStudio 2.13\" and the user says it has three colors (black, white, red). The current code uses `GxEPD2_BW` with `GxEPD2_213_BN`. For tri-color display, we need to use `GxEPD2_3C` with the appropriate display type. But the user wants only black and white, so we need to avoid using any red color commands. The GxEPD2 library's `GxEPD2_3C` can be used but we must only draw black and white, never red. Alternatively, there might be a configuration issue causing red to appear (maybe the display type is wrong or the initial clear is causing a red flash). Let's switch to the proper tri-color type `GxEPD2_213_B73` (which is the 2.13\" tri-color with red) but only use black and white in code. The user says it currently shows red – that's likely because the library defaults to using red for certain operations or the display init causes a red flash. We can force full white refresh first, and ensure we never use red.\n\nBetter approach: keep using `GxEPD2_BW` template but with the correct display class `GxEPD2_213_B73`? Actually, `GxEPD2_BW` is for black & white only panels. For panels that have red, you must use `GxEPD2_3C`. If we try to force B&W on a tri-color panel, it may show garbage or red. So we should use `GxEPD2_3C` with `GxEPD2_213_B73` and simply never use red. All drawing methods accept color: `GxEPD_BLACK`, `GxEPD_WHITE`, and for 3c also `GxEPD_RED`. We'll only use black and white, and the panel should work fine with just two colors (white background, black text). The red will not be used. The current `GxEPD2_BW` with `GxEPD2_213_BN` might actually be the wrong display class for a tri-color screen. `GxEPD2_213_BN` is a B&W-only panel. If he has a tri-color panel, we need something like `GxEPD2_213_B73` (the one with red) or `GxEPD2_213_B74` (the one with yellow? not sure). WeActStudio 2.13\" tri-color should be `GxEPD2_213_B73` based on common usage. So we need to change to `GxEPD2_3C<GxEPD2_213_B73, MAX_HEIGHT>` and use GxEPD_BLACK/GxEPD_WHITE only. That should fix the red issue (red won't be drawn unless we explicitly set text color to red).\n\n2. Remove \"Moisture Monitor\" title to save space for sensor lines.\n\n3. Update display only when values change and use partial update if available.\n\n4. Web UI: fix calibration URLs (they still use old `/api/calibrate/dry/${index}` but the endpoint is now `/api/calibrate/dry?index=${index}`). Also add settings page for WiFi configuration.\n\nLet's address all these.\n\nStep 2: Update Display.h to use GxEPD2_3C with appropriate tri-color type.\n\nStep 3: Update Display.cpp: remove title, implement change detection, partial update.\n\nStep 4: Rewrite index.h: fix API URLs, add WiFi/settings modal.\n\nStep 5: Check WebServer.cpp for any needed changes (e.g., endpoint /api/config/sensor uses query param now). Already done.\n\nLet's start with step 2 (Display.h) since we already read it.\n\nWe also need to read main.cpp to ensure the sensor reading and display update logic is efficient (only update when changed). But we can implement that in Display.cpp (track last drawn values) and in main.cpp we can call display only when readings change. Let's keep it simple: in Display.cpp, store last `sensorCount`, `percentages`, `rawValues`, `wifiStatus` and compare to decide whether to do full or partial update. But partial update on e-paper is tricky – it works but leaves ghosting. For simplicity, we can do full refresh only when labels change (name, wifi), and do a quick partial update for values. Actually, for B&W tri-color, partial update may not be supported. We'll use `m_display.setPartialWindow()` and `m_display.nextPage()` for number updates? The GxEPD2 library supports partial update on most displays by using `setPartialWindow` and then `firstPage`/`nextPage`. But we'd need to track which areas changed. For now, we'll just update only when data changes, using full refresh. To avoid flickering, we can do full refresh only when necessary (e.g., every 10 updates). But the user wants to reduce flashing.\n\nLet's step through.\n\nPlan tasks:\n\n2. Update Display.h: change to GxEPD2_3C<GxEPD2_213_B73, (250 or 122)> or use appropriate template. Actually the height is 250x122. The GxEPD2_3C template takes the display class and page height. So: `GxEPD2_3C<GxEPD2_213_B73, GxEPD2_213_B73::HEIGHT> m_display;` and include <GxEPD2_3C.h>.\n\n3. Update Display.cpp: remove title, track previous values, only call display() if something changed. Use partial window if possible, but full update is acceptable if changes infrequent. The main loop updates display every 10 seconds – that's fine. But we still want to avoid redrawing identical content. So track a hash of the status and skip if same.\n\n4. Update index.h: fix all fetch URLs to use query parameters: `/api/calibrate/dry?index=${index}`, `/api/calibrate/wet?index=${index}`, `/api/calibrate/reset?index=${index}`, `/api/config/sensor?index=${index}`. Also add a settings panel with WiFi configuration (same as captive portal) and sensor name inputs (already there). Add a button to open settings modal. Include fields for SSID and password, and a save button.\n\n5. Since index.h already has name input, we just need to add WiFi settings. We could create a modal overlay.\n\n6. Ensure main.cpp uses Display::showStatus correctly with the new signature (already does). Also ensure that when reading sensors, we call Display only when needed. Already done in main.cpp: display updates every 10 seconds regardless of change. We can keep it simple.\n\nLet's execute.\n\nWe'll first update Display.h, then Display.cpp, then index.h. Then build.",
