        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "We need to fix the Display.h and Display.cpp. The tri-color display type for WeAct 2.13\" with red/black/white is GxEPD2_213_B73 (which is a 3-color display). But GxEPD2 library splits into BW and 3C. The 3C class is for tri-color displays, but we want to only use black/white (ignore red). The issue is that GxEPD2_213_B73 is defined in epd/GxEPD2_213_B73.h and is a class template parameter, but the include path is within GxEPD2_BW.h or GxEPD2_3C.h. Looking at the GxEPD2_BW.h source, it includes `epd/GxEPD2_213_BN.h` (black/white variant). For tri-color, GxEPD2_3C.h includes `epd/GxEPD2_213_B73.h`. So we need to include GxEPD2_3C.h and use GxEPD2_3C instead of GxEPD2_BW.\n\nBut the user says the display is tri-color (black, white, red) and currently it displays red text or backgrounds? They said \"сейчас он почему то красным отображает на экране\" (now it displays red on the screen). This suggests the display is a tri-color variant (like GxEPD2_213_B73) but the code is using GxEPD2_BW, which might be sending incorrect data causing red artifacts, or the display is initialized as black/white but the display has red pixels that show garbage.\n\nTo force black/white only, we can still use the tri-color display class but never send red data (just set red as white). Or use the BW class with the correct panel selection for the tri-color display? Actually, GxEPD2_213_BN is a black/white variant. The user's hardware is likely a tri-color display (like GxEPD2_213_B73). The library includes both: if we use GxEPD2_BW with GxEPD2_213_BN (black/white only) on a tri-color panel, it might still work but could show red remnants.\n\nBetter approach: Use GxEPD2_3C class with GxEPD2_213_B73 but ensure we only use black and white colors. The display might be in 3-color mode but we can still draw only black/white. The red channel will remain white (clear) if we never send red data.\n\nBut the current compilation error: `'GxEPD2_213_B73' was not declared` means the include for that variant is missing. We need to include `GxEPD2_3C.h` and ensure it includes the appropriate variant header (which it does via __has_include).\n\nLet's inspect GxEPD2_3C.h to see if it includes GxEPD2_213_B73 automatically (it should via the same mechanism). The GxEPD2_BW.h includes all variants. GxEPD2_3C.h also should. So we just need to include GxEPD2_3C.h and use GxEPD2_3C template.\n\nBut the user wants black/white only. Maybe simpler: just use GxEPD2_BW with the correct panel for the tri-color display? There is a variant GxEPD2_213_BN (black/white) and GxEPD2_213_B73 (tri-color). Since the hardware is tri-color, we should use GxEPD2_213_B73 but with GxEPD2_3C class. However, we can force black/white by never using red. The red color is set via `setTextColor(GxEPD_RED)` but we never call that.\n\nSo the solution: use GxEPD2_3C<GxEPD2_213_B73, GxEPD2_213_B73::HEIGHT> and include GxEPD2_3C.h.\n\nAlso need to update the constructor in Display.cpp from `GxEPD2_213_BN(...)` to `GxEPD2_213_B73(...)`.\n\nAnd in the begin() we need to call m_display.init(115200, true, 4000000) or similar.\n\nLet's make the changes.\n\nAlso need to remove the red background issue: maybe the display was previously using GxEPD2_BW class but the panel expects tri-color, causing incorrect timing or red pixels to be activated. Switching to the correct class should fix it.\n\nNow, implement the changes.",
