      {
        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "The user wants to optimize the e-ink display refresh strategy. Currently the display refreshes every 10 seconds even if nothing changed, and it does a full partial window refresh rather than only updating changed regions. The main issues are:\n\n1. Too frequent updates (every 10 seconds)\n2. Full partial window refresh instead of only changed parts\n\nI need to redesign the display update logic:\n- Only update display when there's an actual change in data (percentage, raw, wifi status)\n- Use smaller partial windows for individual lines/sensors that changed\n- Increase the display update interval or remove the timer-based update entirely, relying on change detection\n\nLet me plan and then code the solution.\n\nKey changes needed:\n1. In Display::showStatus(), instead of updating the entire partial window, only redraw the entire window when m_firstUpdate is true. For subsequent updates, only update lines that changed based on comparison with m_prevPercentages/m_prevRaw/m_prevWifi.\n\n2. In main.cpp, the display update timer should be less frequent or removed. Currently it's every 10 seconds. I can rely on change detection: display.showStatus() already returns early if nothing changed. But the loop still calls it every 10 seconds, which is okay because it will return early if unchanged. However, a full partial window redraw is still triggered if m_firstUpdate is true.\n\n3. The problem: even when data changes, the current code does a full partial window update (setPartialWindow(0,0,width,height)). For e-ink, partial window updates are still quite slow (a few seconds). To minimize, I should set the partial window to only the region that changed (e.g., a single sensor line). \n\n4. But GxEPD2's partial update mode works best when you set a rectangular region and update only that region. For this tri-color display (GxEPD2_213_Z98c), hasFastPartialUpdate should be true (SSD1680 supports it). We can update individual sensor lines.\n\nLet me implement:\n- Track which sensors changed (percentages[i] != m_prevPercentages[i] || raw[i] != m_prevRaw[i])\n- Also track wifi change\n- If nothing changed, return immediately (done already)\n- If multiple things changed, it might be more efficient to do one larger partial update covering all changed regions\n- Or just update the entire display when any change occurs (simpler and for e-ink it doesn't matter much since entire screen needs to be redrawn)\n\nActually, for e-paper displays, partial update still typically requires updating the entire display buffer and then sending the changed region. The real optimization is to avoid updating when nothing changed. That's already done. The 10-second timer is fine because showStatus() will just return early if nothing changed. The issue may be that the WiFi status changes frequently, or the sensor readings are noisy causing flicker.\n\nLet me also increase the interval to maybe 30 seconds for the timer, and add a check for significant change (percentage changed by more than 1% or raw changed by more than 10).\n\nAlso, I should ensure that showStatus() is not called after calibration/delete operations if the actual values haven't changed. Currently forceFullRefresh sets m_firstUpdate=true, which causes next showStatus() to draw regardless of change. That's correct.\n\nThe user says \"too frequent updates and updates entire screen\". The fix could be:\n1. Increase the display interval to 30 seconds\n2. Add a minimum change threshold\n3. Don't do full partial window, but still the nature of e-ink partial is that it updates the entire buffer visually\n\nI'll proceed with the optimization plan.",
