ut that's unlikely.\n\nI suspect the problem might be that the user hasn't re-flashed, so old firmware still runs old JSON endpoint. But the user is actively testing and reporting bugs, so presumably they flashed after our recent build? We didn't flash, we only built. The user needs to flash. Let me check if we ever flashed. No, we only did `pio run`. The user must manually flash.\n\nHowever, the user may be expecting that after building, the device already has new code. I should explain that they need to re-flash and also maybe add a serial debug message to confirm the new code is running.\n\nAlso, there's a possibility that the ESPAsyncWebServer `hasParam(\"ssid\", true)` has a bug with `true` argument. In the ESPAsyncWebServer library, `hasParam(name, post)` where `post=true` checks POST parameters. The `getParam` also works. This should be fine.\n\nBut maybe the issue is that the request body is not being parsed because the Content-Type header is not exactly `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` (maybe there's a charset). Could use `request->contentType().startsWith(\"application/x-www-form-urlencoded\")` check, but `hasParam` already does parsing.\n\nI think the fix is correct; the user just needs to flash. I'll also add a serial log to help debug.\n\nI'll respond with a clear message: \"I see the endpoint now expects form-urlencoded, and the frontend sends form-urlencoded. The build compiled successfully. Please flash the ESP32 with `pio run -t upload` and then test again. If the problem persists, could you send a screenshot of the exact error message you see?\"",
