        "type": "reasoning",
        "content": "We have a series of tasks: \n\nTask 1: Change pins from GPIO6-10 to GPIO1-5 in src/main.cpp → DONE.\nTask 2: Add HTTP authentication to WebServer.cpp → DONE (conceptually, but need to verify actual code changes were applied).\nTask 3: Fix XSS in index.h → Not yet done.\nTask 4: Check return values of begin() → Not yet done.\nTask 5: Extract magic numbers → Not yet done.\nTask 6: Read remaining files → Not yet done.\n\nThe code agent returned \"Need to see the createOrUpdateSensorCard function...\" but we already have that content from read-file results. The agent didn't make the edit. Probably the agent is not seeing the file content because it needs to read it itself. I need to be explicit.\n\nI can do the XSS fix directly with a patch or write the corrected code. Let me write the fix directly. I will replace the innerHTML block with safe element creation. Since the code agent might not be able to handle large edits, I can use the \"patch\" tool or write file with custom content.\n\nBut the instruction says: NEVER use shell for file editing, use {\"type\":\"code\"} for all file changes. But using {\"type\":\"code\"} seems to be failing. Maybe I should use {\"type\":\"tool\",\"toolName\":\"patch\"} with exact string replacement.\n\nI can replace the exact innerHTML template with safe creation. Let me compose the new function part.\n\nFrom lines 479-501:\n\n```javascript\n  function createOrUpdateSensorCard(index, data) {\n    let card = cards[index];\n    if (!card) {\n      card = document.createElement('div');\n      card.className = 'card';\n      card.innerHTML = `\n        <input class=\"name-input\" id=\"name-${index}\" value=\"${data.name || ''}\" />\n        <div class=\"gauge-wrapper\">\n          <div class=\"gauge\">\n            <svg viewBox=\"0 0 100 100\">\n              <circle class=\"bg\" cx=\"50\" cy=\"50\" r=\"46\"/>\n              <circle class=\"fg\" id=\"gauge-${index}\" cx=\"50\" cy=\"50\" r=\"46\" stroke-dasharray=\"${circumference}\" stroke-dashoffset=\"${circumference}\"/>\n            </svg>\n            <div class=\"gauge-value\" id=\"gauge-value-${index}\">0%</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"metrics\">\n          <div class=\"metric\"><span class=\"label\">Raw</span><span class=\"value\" id=\"raw-${index}\">${data.raw}</span></div>\n          <div class=\"metric\"><span class=\"label\">V</span><span class=\"value\" id=\"voltage-${index}\">${data.voltage}V</span></div>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"btn-group\" id=\"btns-${index}\"></div>\n      `;\n      sensorContainer.appendChild(card);\n      cards[index] = card;\n      const nameInput = card.querySelector(`#name-${index}`);\n      nameInput.addEventListener('change', function() {\n        const newName = this.value.trim();\n        if (!newName) return;\n        fetch(`/api/config/sensor?index=${index}`, {\n          method: 'POST',\n          headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},\n          body: JSON.stringify({name: newName})\n        }).then(() => {\n          messageDiv.textContent = 'Name updated for sensor ' + index;\n          setTimeout(() => { messageDiv.textContent = ''; }, 2000);\n        }).catch(() => { messageDiv.textContent = 'Error updating name'; });\n      });\n    }\n```\n\nI need to replace this entire block (from `if (!card) {` to after the closing `}` of that if block) with safe DOM creation. The safe approach: create each element using document.createElement, set textContent, then append them. However, building a nested DOM structure with JS is verbose. Alternatively, we can still use innerHTML for the static parts but escape the dynamic values. But the safest approach is to use template literal with escaping via a function that replaces HTML special characters.\n\nBetter: define a function `escapeHtml(str)` and use it in the template literal. That way we keep the simple template but prevent XSS.\n\nI'll add a small `escapeHtml` function and modify the innerHTML line to escape `data.name`, `data.raw`, `data.voltage`.\n\nThat is a minimal change:\n\n```javascript\nconst escapeHtml = (unsafe) => {\n  return unsafe.replace(/&/g, '&amp;').replace(/</g, '&lt;').replace(/>/g, '&gt;').replace(/\"/g, '&quot;').replace(/'/g, '&#039;');\n};\n```\n\nThen modify line 485: `value=\"${escapeHtml(data.name || '')}\"`  \nLine 496: `<span class=\"value\" id=\"raw-${index}\">${escapeHtml(data.raw)}</span>`  \nLine 497: `<span class=\"value\" id=\"voltage-${index}\">${escapeHtml(data.voltage)}V</span>`\n\nI will use the patch tool to apply these changes. Let me first try to patch the exact lines.\n\nFrom the read-file, line 479-501 exactly as shown. I'll create a patch to replace that block with one that includes `escapeHtml` and uses it.\n\nBut using patch with exact string may fail due to whitespace differences. Alternatively, use code agent with explicit instruction.\n\nGiven that code agent is returning without changes, I'll use patch directly.\n\nI'll construct a patch for the innerHTML line and add escapeHtml function.\n\nBut I need to add the function at the top of the IIFE. I'll patch line 464-465 to include the function.\n\nLet me do it step by step: first add escapeHtml, then fix the innerHTML lines.\n\nI'll use multiple patch calls or one patch that covers multiple changes. Patch supports two strings: oldString and newString. I can replace the old block with new block.\n\nI'll create a patch that replaces the entire `function createOrUpdateSensorCard...` block? That's large and might have whitespace issues. Better to target the specific lines.\n\nI'll use `patch` on the file with the following old/new strings.\n\nFirst, add escapeHtml function after line 464 (or before line 471). Let's insert after line 464: `const circumference = ...`.\n\nOld:\n```\n  const circumference = 2 * Math.PI * 46;\n  const messageDiv = document.getElementById('message');\n```\nNew:\n```\n  const circumference = 2 * Math.PI * 46;\n  const escapeHtml