497: change `${data.raw}` and `${data.voltage}` to `${escapeHtml(data.raw)}` and `${escapeHtml(data.voltage)}`\n\nI'll combine patches. Or use one patch to replace lines 484-500 with a corrected version.\n\nBetter: patch the entire innerHTML string block (lines 484-500) with the escaped version. Use exact old string from the file.\n\nLet me construct the old string exactly as it appears (including backticks and newlines). I'll copy from the file content.\n\nThe old string starts at line 484: `card.innerHTML = \\`` and ends at line 500: `` `; ``\n\nBut to avoid large patch, I can just target the three specific lines.\n\nI'll do three patches sequentially.\n\nBut careful: after each patch, the file changes, so subsequent patches need to match the new content. Safer to do one patch that covers all changes.\n\nI'll use a single patch that replaces a block from `const circumference = ...` to just after the createOrUpdateSensorCard function? That's too large.\n\nI'll use two patches: one to add escapeHtml, another to replace the innerHTML block.\n\nLet me try: first add escapeHtml with a focused patch. Then replace the innerHTML template lines.\n\nI'll start with patch for the escapeHtml insertion.\n\nBut to avoid failures due to whitespace, I'll use exact character match. Let me get the current file state by reading again just in case. But I just read lines 460-559, so I have the current content.\n\nI'll proceed with code agent but with very explicit instructions and the exact code to use. If that doesn't work, I'll fallback to patch.\n\nGiven that the code agent keeps returning \"Need to see...\", I think the agent is not reading the file effectively. I can instruct it more strongly: \"I have already read the file. Here is the current content for the relevant section: ...  Make the following changes exactly: ...\"\n\nLet me try that.",
